    {
      "id": "8161023382a622e34e2038f808a706b8713780f7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2014-07-09 19:38:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nYes, it is good to know if clients are being evicted, but this does *not* necessarily mean the console is the place to perform this notification.\n\nA server's console log is most certainly *not* the place to perform filesystem monitoring.\n\nI vehemently disagree with the concept that we should be outputting a message to a server's console for normal operating behavior of the filesystem. If the admin simply wants to know that evictions are occurring (e.g. monitor eviction activity), the console log is *not* the correct place to do this. Instead, we should have an actual service/utility/etc that can be used to monitor the system(s). \n\nWith that said, I doubt this will land (it's been in progress for nearly 2 years!); and I've honestly lost hope that Lustre will ever get better in this regard.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
